data:
Developing Good Practice in Safeguarding Students is a mobility project for Vocational Education and Training (VET) staff working for the Association of Colleges (AoC) or one of its English member colleges.  The project will provide four three-day study visits, two of which will be focused on mental health and student wellbeing and two of which will focus on the English VET system's work around the national Prevent duty which aims to take a due regard to the need to prevent people from being drawn into terrorism.  Both focus areas are a high priority for AoC and it's member colleges.

Mental health support has recently been given much higher profile nationally with the government announcement that there would be a Green Paper on mental health support for young people.  Increasing, AoC  and it's members have seen the rise in mental health problems in our students.  AoC has led the development of a Mental Health Resource Pack its members and has formed a national Mental Health Advisory Group to support initiatives and mental health strategies.

The Prevent Duty is a mandatory part of the OfSTED Inspection for Further Education (FE) colleges.  Surrounding this, however, are the wider issues that support Prevent in FE colleges - namely equality and diversity, inclusion and safeguarding.  Colleges within the AoC membership have appointed Prevent co-ordinators whose responsibility it is to undertake to develop and deliver Prevent training to colleagues at all levels across the organisation.

Both areas of focus are issues that our EU partners face.  In Sweden, we are partnering with Gothenburg and Stockholm schools with large, ethnically diverse student populations, where they share many of the challenges of those in the UK, but they also face particular issues such as defection to Syria in Sweden within the locality of both colleges.  Both Dutch and Finnish partners also recognise the challenges increasingly faced by students within their schools and the important role that schools and colleges have in supporting young people with mental health challenges to enable them to complete their studies and take a happy and active role in society.

The objectives of the study visits in this project are to enable those tasked with these areas of focus within their work in colleges (or at AoC) to learn about the challenges faced in partner countries, share experience and expertise and identify new approaches to these very important areas of work.

60 participants will be drawn from AoC member colleges and the AoC staff team (15 participants per study visit).  Member college participants will all have a responsibility for safeguarding and Prevent or mental health and wellbeing and AoC staff team members will all be working within a policy setting around the two focus areas to ensure maximum benefit both individually and at a wider level.

The main activities will be the four study visit programmes, taking place across two academic years, in either Sweden, the Netherlands or Finland.  Each study visit will include a national overview of the VET system in each country and of the specific challenges around safeguarding, preventing radicalisation and equality and diversity or mental health support and wellbeing, visits to hosting partner colleges to meet and talk to staff engaged in these areas of work, gain an understanding of the local environment where colleges are based, finishing with a joint peer learning workshop with best practice case study presenters from both sides and round table discussions.

In terms of intended outcomes we envisage that these will be the opportunity to:
*Share/gain knowledge around either equality diversity, preventing extremism/radicalisation and or supporting students with mental health and wellbeing issues;
*Spend time away from the workplace with other UK participants who have a similar remit allowing for reflection on practice, the chance for discussion on national strategy and a group approach to discussions with EU partners;
*Visit partner colleges, understand the context in which they are working and the learning environment;
*Hear other countries' national strategies/directives around the key issues through briefings from national experts;
*Engage in a peer learning workshop with Dutch, Swedish or Finnish staff who are implementing strategies within their colleges;
*Forge professional partnerships for continued dialogue around this area of work;
*Find potential partners for further EU partnership work.

Potential longer term benefits include:
*Cultural understanding of another EU country and promoting EU experience to other staff and learners as a means to increasing skills and knowledge and potential future EU project partnerships;
*The embedding of EU examples of best practice into Prevent and Safeguarding or Mental Health support training for staff across colleges;
*More informed relationships for AoC and colleges with key government departments around these key priority areas.
